<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-713-799  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 713 799.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>LAN Times  Dec 10 1990 v7 n15 p60(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Imaging offers new ways to use documents on LANs: the softwarebehind this is fully network based.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Ruiz, David E.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Document imaging systems, which facilitate automation ofpaper-intensive business functions, offer a wide range ofcapabilities for processing and manipulating documents on anetwork, including capture, storage and management functions.andO;Document imaging systems offer both direct and indirect costbenefits.andP;  An organization considering implementation of animaging system should select an application that is clearlyunderstood by all parties to be involved in its use and one whichoffers a clear cost-benefit justification.andP;  Clear functional andsystem interface limits for the system and key operationalmilestones and acceptance criteria must be established to assistin managing the expectations of users, administrators andmanagement.andP;  A strong project team comprising representatives fromboth the end-user and MIS communities must be established andempowered to ensure the success of the application.andP;  Currentdocument imaging systems mirror the paper-based systems they areequivalent to; future systems, incorporating multimediatechnology, will establish the imaging industry as a sector of thesoftware industry.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Document Management SystemsImage ProcessingOutlookAnalysisTrends.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   Typical workgroup configuration with image processing. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>